@node Setting TODO properties
@subsection Setting TODO properties

@findex org-extras-set-todo-properties
When triaging tasks, it is common to assign both a priority and an
effort estimate in quick succession.  The command
@code{org-extras-set-todo-properties} calls @code{org-priority} followed by
@code{org-set-effort}, saving a keystroke sequence.

@node Copying URLs and links
@subsection Copying URLs and links

@findex org-extras-url-dwim
@findex org-extras-link-get-link-at-point
@findex org-extras-link-get-url-at-point
@findex org-extras-link-get-description-at-point
Org buffers frequently contain both plain URLs and bracketed Org links,
and one often needs to extract a piece of a link for use elsewhere.  The
command @code{org-extras-url-dwim} copies the URL at point to the kill ring,
handling both plain URLs (detected via @code{thing-at-point-url-at-point})
and the target of an Org bracket link.

For more targeted extraction, three additional commands operate on
bracket links: @code{org-extras-link-get-link-at-point} copies the full
bracket link syntax, @code{org-extras-link-get-url-at-point} copies only the
URL portion, and @code{org-extras-link-get-description-at-point} copies only
the description portion.  All three use @code{org-extras-link-get-thing-at-point}
internally (@ref{Link helpers}).

@node Removing links
@subsection Removing links

@findex org-extras-remove-link
The command @code{org-extras-remove-link} replaces an Org bracket link at
point with its description text, or with its URL if the link has no
description.  This is handy when you want to keep the display text but
strip the hyperlink markup.

@node Inserting subheadings
@subsection Inserting subheadings

@findex org-extras-insert-todo-subheading-after-body
@findex org-extras-insert-subheading
Org provides @code{org-insert-heading} and @code{org-insert-todo-heading}, but
inserting a subheading at exactly the right position often requires
several manual steps.  The command
@code{org-extras-insert-todo-subheading-after-body} narrows to the current
subtree, hides its children, moves to the end, and inserts a demoted
TODO heading.  The result is a new TODO subheading at the very end of
the current entry.

The command @code{org-extras-insert-subheading} is similar but inserts a
plain (non-TODO) subheading.  It places the new heading after the
current entry's body but before any existing subheadings, which is
useful when you want to add prose subsections above the task list.

@node Copying heading contents and names
@subsection Copying heading contents and names

@findex org-extras-copy-heading-contents
@findex org-extras-copy-heading-name
The command @code{org-extras-copy-heading-contents} copies the body text of
the heading at point (excluding the heading line itself and any child
subtrees) to the kill ring.  It uses @code{org-extras-get-heading-contents}
internally (@ref{Heading content helpers}).  If the heading has no body
text, a message is displayed instead.

The command @code{org-extras-copy-heading-name} copies the heading title
(without stars, TODO keyword, priority, or tags) to the kill ring.

@node Counting words
@subsection Counting words

@findex org-extras-count-words
The command @code{org-extras-count-words} counts words in the active region
if one exists, falling back to counting words across the entire current
subtree (including child entries) when no region is active.  In subtree
mode, it skips metadata at the beginning of each entry.  The word count
is copied to the kill ring and a summary message is displayed showing
lines, words, and characters.

@node Jumping to the first heading
@subsection Jumping to the first heading

@findex org-extras-jump-to-first-heading
The command @code{org-extras-jump-to-first-heading} widens the buffer and
moves point to the first visible Org heading.  Several other functions
in this package call it internally (for example,
@code{org-extras-capture-before-finalize-hook-function}).

@node Opening links in EWW
@subsection Opening links in EWW

@findex org-extras-super-return
The command @code{org-extras-super-return} opens the Org link at point using
EWW rather than the default system browser.  It temporarily binds
@code{browse-url-browser-function} to @code{eww-browse-url} and clears
@code{browse-url-handlers} before calling @code{org-open-at-point}.  This is
useful when you want to preview a web page without leaving Emacs.

@node Pasting clipboard content as Org
@subsection Pasting clipboard content as Org

@findex org-extras-paste-with-conversion
The command @code{org-extras-paste-with-conversion} converts the contents of
the system clipboard to Org mode format using Pandoc and inserts the
result at point.  If the clipboard contains HTML, it converts from HTML;
otherwise it converts from Markdown.  The command also cleans up stray
backslashes and non-breaking spaces that Pandoc sometimes produces.

Internally it calls @code{simple-extras-pandoc-convert} from @samp{simple-extras.el}.
For the reverse operation (copying Org as formatted HTML), see
@code{ox-clip-formatted-copy}.  For the Markdown equivalent, see
@code{markdown-mode-extras-paste-with-conversion} in @samp{markdown-mode-extras.el}.

@node Pasting images from the clipboard
@subsection Pasting images from the clipboard

@findex org-extras-paste-image
The command @code{org-extras-paste-image} saves the current clipboard image
to a file and inserts an Org file link at point.  It requires the
@samp{pngpaste} utility (installable via @samp{brew install pngpaste} on macOS).

The image is saved under @code{paths-dir-org-images} with a filename derived
from the current heading's Org ID and an incrementing counter to avoid
collisions.  After saving, the command prompts for an optional caption
and then calls @code{org-display-inline-images} to render the image inline.

@node Toggling inline images
@subsection Toggling inline images

@findex org-extras-inline-images
The command @code{org-extras-inline-images} toggles the display of inline
images in the current buffer.  When called interactively without a
prefix argument, it checks whether any inline image overlays already
exist: if they do, it removes them; otherwise it displays all images.

A numeric prefix argument provides explicit control: a negative value
removes images, while a positive value (or @code{nil} from Lisp) displays
them.  The symbol @code{toggle} may also be passed from Lisp for the
toggling behavior.

