@node Switching to today's agenda
@subsection Switching to today's agenda

@findex org-extras-agenda-switch-to-agenda-current-day
The command @code{org-extras-agenda-switch-to-agenda-current-day} opens (or
switches to) the daily agenda in the left window of the frame.  It
calls @code{window-extras-split-if-unsplit} from @samp{window-extras.el} to
ensure the frame is split, then selects window 1 via @samp{winum}.  If the
agenda buffer already exists, it simply switches to it; otherwise it
creates a new agenda view, first enabling anniversary display
(@ref{Toggling anniversaries}).

@node Going to an agenda item and clocking in
@subsection Going to an agenda item and clocking in

@findex org-extras-agenda-goto-and-start-clock
The command @code{org-extras-agenda-goto-and-start-clock} navigates from the
Org agenda buffer to the source heading of the item at point and starts
the clock there.  It validates the agenda marker and offers to refresh
the agenda if the marker is stale.  This command must be called from an
@code{org-agenda-mode} buffer.

@node Marking done and postponing
@subsection Marking done and postponing

@findex org-extras-agenda-done-and-next
@findex org-extras-agenda-postpone-and-next
Two quick-action commands streamline common agenda operations.  The
command @code{org-extras-agenda-done-and-next} marks the item at point as
DONE and advances to the next line.  The command
@code{org-extras-agenda-postpone-and-next} pushes the scheduled date forward
by one day and advances to the next line.  Both are designed for rapid
triage of agenda items.

@node DWIM switching from agenda
@subsection DWIM switching from agenda

@findex org-extras-agenda-switch-to-dwim
The command @code{org-extras-agenda-switch-to-dwim} adapts its behavior based
on whether the agenda is showing log entries.  When
@code{org-agenda-show-log} is active, it calls
@code{org-clock-convenience-goto-ts} to jump to the clock timestamp in the
source file.  When log mode is off, it calls @code{org-agenda-switch-to} to
open the heading directly.

@node Toggling anniversaries
@subsection Toggling anniversaries

@findex org-extras-agenda-toggle-anniversaries
The command @code{org-extras-agenda-toggle-anniversaries} shows or hides BBDB
birthday entries in the agenda.  It works by navigating to the heading
specified by @code{org-extras-bbdb-anniversaries-heading}
(@ref{BBDB anniversaries heading}) and toggling the
@samp{%%(org-bbdb-anniversaries-future 1)} sexp line: if the line is present
it is deleted, and if it is absent it is inserted.  Unless the optional
JUST-ENABLE argument is non-nil, the agenda is refreshed afterwards.

This approach of commenting out the diary sexp is the only reliable way
to temporarily suppress anniversaries in the weekly/daily agenda view.

@node Toggling log mode
@subsection Toggling log mode

@findex org-extras-agenda-toggle-log-mode
The command @code{org-extras-agenda-toggle-log-mode} toggles
@code{org-agenda-log-mode} in clock-check mode, which shows or hides clock
entries in the agenda.

@node Removing agenda highlighting
@subsection Removing agenda highlighting

@findex org-extras-unhighlight
The command @code{org-extras-unhighlight} is a thin interactive wrapper
around @code{org-unhighlight}, which removes search highlighting from the
agenda buffer.

@node Clocking and timestamps
@section Clocking and timestamps

@menu
* Inserting clock entries::
* Inserting timestamps::
* Jumping to clock entries::
* Clock reports::
* Deleting headings without logbooks::
* Meeting participants::
@end menu

@node Inserting clock entries
@subsection Inserting clock entries

@findex org-extras-new-clock-entry-today
The command @code{org-extras-new-clock-entry-today} inserts a new CLOCK line
under the current heading with today's date.  It prompts for a begin
time and an end time (as strings such as @samp{"09:00"}), then jumps to the
latest existing clock entry via @code{org-extras-jump-to-latest-clock-entry}
(@ref{Jumping to clock entries}), opens a line above it, inserts the
formatted clock range, and evaluates the time range to compute the
duration.

@node Inserting timestamps
@subsection Inserting timestamps

@findex org-extras-time-stamp-active-current-time
@findex org-extras-time-stamp-inactive-current-time
@findex org-extras-time-stamp-active-current-date
@findex org-extras-time-stamp-inactive-current-date
Four commands insert timestamps with the current date or date-and-time:

@itemize
@item
@code{org-extras-time-stamp-active-current-time} inserts an active
timestamp with date and time, e.g. @samp{<2025-01-15 Wed 14:30>}.
@item
@code{org-extras-time-stamp-inactive-current-time} inserts an inactive
timestamp with date and time, e.g. @samp{[2025-01-15 Wed 14:30]}.
@item
@code{org-extras-time-stamp-active-current-date} inserts an active
timestamp with date only, e.g. @samp{<2025-01-15 Wed>}.
@item
@code{org-extras-time-stamp-inactive-current-date} inserts an inactive
timestamp with date only, e.g. @samp{[2025-01-15 Wed]}.
@end itemize

These are convenient when you need a timestamp at the current moment
without being prompted by the Org date picker.

@node Jumping to clock entries
@subsection Jumping to clock entries

@findex org-extras-jump-to-latest-clock-entry
The command @code{org-extras-jump-to-latest-clock-entry} enables
@code{visible-mode}, shows the logbook drawer via @code{org-extras-show-logbook}
(@ref{Showing drawers}), moves back to the current heading, and then
searches forward for the first CLOCK line.  Since clock entries are
stored in reverse chronological order, this effectively jumps to the
most recent clock entry.

@node Clock reports
@subsection Clock reports

@findex org-extras-clock-report-insert
The command @code{org-extras-clock-report-insert} prompts for a start date,
an end date, and a scope (@samp{agenda}, @samp{file}, or @samp{subtree}), then
inserts a clocktable dynamic block using the format string in
@code{org-extras-clock-report-parameters} (@ref{Clock report parameters}).
If the start and end dates are the same, a @samp{:block} parameter is used;
otherwise @samp{:tstart} and @samp{:tend} are used.  The clocktable is updated
immediately after insertion.

@node Deleting headings without logbooks
@subsection Deleting headings without logbooks

@findex org-extras-delete-headings-without-logbook
The command @code{org-extras-delete-headings-without-logbook} removes every
heading in the current buffer that does not contain a @samp{:LOGBOOK:}
drawer.  It prompts for confirmation before proceeding.  This is useful
for cleaning up files where only clocked entries are of interest.

@node Meeting participants
@subsection Meeting participants

@findex org-extras-add-participants
@findex org-extras-clock-in-add-participants
When clocking into a calendar event (a heading with a @samp{calendar-id}
property), it is useful to record who attended.  The function
@code{org-extras-clock-in-add-participants} is installed as @samp{:after} advice
on @code{org-clock-in}.  When the heading has a @samp{calendar-id} property and
does not already list participants (checked via
@code{org-extras-heading-has-participans-p}), it calls
@code{org-extras-add-participants}.  Headings matching the regexp in
@code{org-extras-clock-in-add-participants-exclude} are skipped
(@ref{Participant exclusion regexp}).

The command @code{org-extras-add-participants} can also be called
interactively.  It presents a @code{completing-read-multiple} prompt
populated with ``person'' nodes from Org Roam (via
@code{org-roam-extras-get-people} in @samp{org-roam-extras.el}), formats the
selected names as Org ID links, and inserts a ``Participants: @dots{}'' line
after the heading's metadata.

@node Folding cycling and narrowing
@section Folding, cycling, and narrowing

@menu
* Global cycling::
* Showing all headings::
* Showing drawers::
* Narrowing to entries::
@end menu

@node Global cycling
@subsection Global cycling

@findex org-extras-cycle-global
The command @code{org-extras-cycle-global} calls @code{org-cycle-global} and then
hides archived subtrees via @code{org-cycle-hide-archived-subtrees}.  Without
this, global cycling would reveal archived content that is normally meant
to stay hidden.  An optional prefix argument ARG works the same way as
in @code{org-cycle-global}: @samp{C-u} switches to startup visibility, a numeric
prefix shows all headlines up to that level.

@node Showing all headings
@subsection Showing all headings

@findex org-extras-fold-show-all-headings
The function @code{org-extras-fold-show-all-headings} expands all headings in
the buffer (using @code{org-fold-show-all} with the @samp{headings} argument)
while keeping archived subtrees hidden.  This is not an interactive
command but is designed to be called from hooks or other functions.

@node Showing drawers
@subsection Showing drawers

@findex org-extras-show-properties
@findex org-extras-show-logbook
The command @code{org-extras-show-properties} removes all overlays that hide
property drawers (those with the @samp{hidden-prop-drawer} property),
making them visible again.  It also updates the toggle state to
@samp{shown}.

The command @code{org-extras-show-logbook} does the same for logbook drawers
(overlays with the @samp{hidden-logbook-drawer} property).  Both commands are
useful after running packages that hide these drawers by default.

@node Narrowing to entries
@subsection Narrowing to entries

@findex org-extras-narrow-to-entry-and-children
@findex org-extras-narrow-to-entry-no-children
The command @code{org-extras-narrow-to-entry-and-children} narrows the buffer
to the current subtree and then shows the entry and its children while
hiding drawers (via @code{org-extras-show-subtree-hide-drawers}).  This gives
a focused view of the heading and all its descendants.

The command @code{org-extras-narrow-to-entry-no-children} narrows the buffer
to the current entry only, excluding any subheadings.  The narrowed
region extends from the beginning of the subtree to the next visible
heading.

@node ID management
@section ID management

@menu
* Automatic ID addition::
* Updating ID locations::
* Finding duplicate IDs::
* Processing duplicate IDs::
@end menu

@node Automatic ID addition
@subsection Automatic ID addition

@findex org-extras-id-auto-add-ids-to-headings-in-file
The function @code{org-extras-id-auto-add-ids-to-headings-in-file} is
intended to run from a hook (such as @code{before-save-hook}).  It adds Org
IDs to all headings in the current file that lack them, subject to
several exclusion conditions:

@itemize
@item
The file must be in @code{org-mode} and within @code{paths-dir-org}.
@item
The buffer must not be read-only.
@item
The buffer-local variable @code{org-extras-id-auto-add-exclude-file} must
be @code{nil} (@ref{Variables}).
@item
The file must not be inside a directory listed in
@code{org-extras-id-auto-add-excluded-directories}.
@item
The file must not match @code{org-extras-id-auto-add-excluded-files}.
@item
The current heading must not match
@code{org-extras-id-auto-add-excluded-headings}.
@item
For files in directories listed in
@code{org-extras-id-auto-add-level-1-dirs}, only level-1 headings receive
IDs.
@end itemize

See @ref{Automatic ID exclusions} for details on configuring
these options.

@node Updating ID locations
@subsection Updating ID locations

@findex org-extras-id-update-id-locations
The command @code{org-extras-id-update-id-locations} scans all @samp{.org} and
@samp{.org.gpg} files under @code{org-directory} (excluding those in @samp{.Trash}
directories or with carriage returns in their names) and updates the ID
location database via @code{org-id-update-id-locations}.  If the scan
reports duplicate IDs, the command automatically calls
@code{org-extras-id-find-duplicate-ids} (@ref{Finding duplicate IDs}) so
that you can review and resolve them.

Internally, it temporarily advises @code{display-warning} to intercept
``duplicate IDs found'' messages and trigger the duplicate-ID workflow.

@node Finding duplicate IDs
@subsection Finding duplicate IDs

@findex org-extras-id-find-duplicate-ids
The command @code{org-extras-id-find-duplicate-ids} parses the @samp{*Messages*}
buffer for ``Duplicate ID'' warnings produced by
@code{org-id-update-id-locations} and presents the results in a dedicated
read-only @samp{*Duplicate Org IDs*} buffer.  Each line shows a file path
followed by the duplicate ID@.  In this buffer, pressing @samp{SPC} calls
@code{org-extras-id-process-next-duplicate} to process the next entry.

@node Processing duplicate IDs
@subsection Processing duplicate IDs

@findex org-extras-id-process-next-duplicate
The command @code{org-extras-id-process-next-duplicate} is meant to be used
from the @samp{*Duplicate Org IDs*} buffer.  It reads the first line, opens
the associated file, widens the buffer, enables
@code{simple-extras-visible-mode-enhanced} to help locate the duplicate,
copies the ID to the kill ring, and removes the processed line from the
buffer.  When all entries have been processed, the buffer is killed
automatically.

@node List handling
@section List handling

@findex org-extras-mark-checkbox-complete-and-move-to-next-item
@findex org-extras-reset-checkbox-state-subtree
The command @code{org-extras-mark-checkbox-complete-and-move-to-next-item}
toggles the checkbox state at point (equivalent to @samp{C-c C-c}) and then
moves to the next list item.  This enables rapid checkbox processing
with a single repeated keystroke.

The command @code{org-extras-reset-checkbox-state-subtree} resets all
checkboxes in the current subtree to their unchecked state, then cycles
the subtree visibility twice to ensure a clean display without exposed
property drawers.

@node Refiling
@section Refiling

@menu
* Jumping to the latest refiled item::
* Refiling and archiving::
* Regenerating the refile cache::
@end menu

@node Jumping to the latest refiled item
@subsection Jumping to the latest refiled item

@findex org-extras-refile-goto-latest
The command @code{org-extras-refile-goto-latest} widens the buffer and calls
@code{org-refile} with a double prefix argument (@samp{C-u C-u}), which jumps to
the location of the most recently refiled item.  This is helpful when
you refile something and immediately want to continue working on it in
its new location.

@node Refiling and archiving
@subsection Refiling and archiving

@findex org-extras-refile-and-archive
The command @code{org-extras-refile-and-archive} performs two operations in
sequence: it refiles the current subtree (prompting for a target as
usual), then navigates to the refiled heading and archives it to its
archive sibling.  This is useful when an item has been completed and
should be both relocated and archived in one step.

@node Regenerating the refile cache
@subsection Regenerating the refile cache

@findex org-extras-refile-regenerate-cache
The command @code{org-extras-refile-regenerate-cache} clears the existing
@code{org-refile} target cache and rebuilds it from scratch.  This is needed
when refile targets have changed (files added, headings renamed) and the
cached completions are stale.

@node Links and sorting
@section Links and sorting

@menu
* Sorting links::
* Copying EWW content as Org::
@end menu

@node Sorting links
@subsection Sorting links

@findex org-extras-sort-links
@findex org-extras-sort-keywords
The command @code{org-extras-sort-links} sorts a paragraph of Org links
alphabetically.  It prompts for the separator string used between links
(for example, @samp{", "} or @samp{" | "}), splits the paragraph text on that
separator, sorts the resulting elements using @code{org-sort-list}, and
reassembles them.

The command @code{org-extras-sort-keywords} is a convenience wrapper that
calls @code{org-extras-sort-links} with the separator @samp{" . "} (bullet
separator), which is the convention used for keyword lists.

@node Copying EWW content as Org
@subsection Copying EWW content as Org

@findex org-extras-eww-copy-for-org-mode
The command @code{org-extras-eww-copy-for-org-mode} copies the content of an
EWW buffer (or the active region within it) to the kill ring, converting
HTML formatting to Org syntax.  Links become Org bracket links, bold
text is wrapped in @samp{*asterisks*}, italic text in @samp{/slashes/}, and HTML
bullet characters are replaced with Org list markers (@samp{-}).

This is an enhanced version of @code{org-eww-copy-for-org-mode} from the
@samp{ol-eww} library.

@node Babel and encryption
@section Babel and encryption

@menu
* Tangling::
* Decryption and clock evaluation::
@end menu

@node Tangling
@subsection Tangling

@findex org-extras-babel-tangle
The command @code{org-extras-babel-tangle} widens the buffer, saves it, and
then tangles all source blocks via @code{org-babel-tangle}.  Widening first
ensures that narrowed buffers are tangled completely.

@node Decryption and clock evaluation
@subsection Decryption and clock evaluation

@findex org-extras-crypt-dwim
The command @code{org-extras-crypt-dwim} inspects the Org element at point.
If point is on a clock line, it evaluates the time range (computing the
duration).  Otherwise, it decrypts the current entry via
@code{org-decrypt-entry}.  This DWIM behavior avoids the need for separate
key bindings for these two contextually distinct actions.  The command
signals an error if invoked outside an Org mode buffer.

@node External integration
@section External integration

@menu
* Importing from Google Drive::
* Removing trailing headings::
@end menu

@node Importing from Google Drive
@subsection Importing from Google Drive

@findex org-extras-import-from-google-drive
The command @code{org-extras-import-from-google-drive} prompts for a Google
Doc ID, downloads the document as a @samp{.docx} file using the @samp{gdrive} CLI
tool, and converts it to Org format using Pandoc.  Both output files are
saved in the downloads directory (@code{paths-dir-downloads}).  To find the
Doc ID, run @samp{gdrive list} in a terminal.

@node Removing trailing headings
@subsection Removing trailing headings

@findex org-extras-remove-trailing-heading
The command @code{org-extras-remove-trailing-heading} removes the last
heading in the buffer if it is empty (has no heading text).  This is
intended for use as a hook function (for example, via a directory-local
variable) in directories such as @samp{gptel} notes, where automated
processes sometimes create spurious empty headings that trigger warnings
from @code{org-roam}.

@node Transient menus
@section Transient menus

@findex org-extras-personal-menu
@findex org-extras-tlon-menu
@findex org-extras-config-dispatch
@samp{org-extras.el} provides three transient menus for quick navigation to
frequently visited Org Roam nodes and configuration sections.

The command @code{org-extras-personal-menu} opens a menu of personal projects
and recurring tasks, including entries for email, finance, Anki,
YouTube, and language study.  Each menu item navigates to a specific Org
Roam node by ID@.

The command @code{org-extras-tlon-menu} opens a menu organized into three
columns: languages (with two-letter language codes as keys), projects
(such as @samp{aea}, @samp{boletin}, @samp{utilitarianism}), and other items.  This
is designed for navigating the Tlon project ecosystem.

The command @code{org-extras-config-dispatch} opens a menu for jumping to
sections within the main @samp{config.org} file.  It includes entries for
major configuration areas (Calc, Dired, Elfeed, Files, Display, and so
on) as well as Org-specific subsections (org-agenda, org-capture,
org-roam, and others).

